Maybe the closed form expression implies this?

$$
\sum_n (A^n - B^n)/(\sqrt{5}) x^n
=
\sum_n ((Ax)^n - (Bx)^n)/\sqrt(5)
=
(1/\sqrt{5})
\times
\left(
\frac{Ax}{1-Ax}
-
\frac{Bx}{1-Bx}
\right)
$$

For $x=1/2$,
$$
(1/2)
(1/\sqrt(5))
(
(1/2)(1+\sqrt{5})/(1-(1+sqrt(5)/2)(1/2))
-
(1/2)(1-\sqrt{5})/(1-(1-sqrt(5)/2)(1/2))
)
$$

Look at
$$
(1+\sqrt{5})(1-(1-\sqrt{5})/4)
-
(1-\sqrt{5})(1-(1+\sqrt{5})/4)
=
1+\sqrt{5} - (1-\sqrt{5})
-
(1+\sqrt{5})(1-\sqrt{5})/4
+
(1-\sqrt{5})(1+\sqrt{5})/4
=
2\sqrt{5} \; .
$$

## Again

Need
$$
5p^2+4
$$
a square, in which case find $q$ by
$$
q^2 - pq - p^2 - 1 = 0
=>
q = (p + \sqrt{5p^2+4})/2
$$
